The Presidential Council for Human Rights (HRC), on behalf of Vladimir Putin, has developed proposals to strengthen the independence of the judiciary.
The HRC proposes that the powers of the presidents of the courts be limited and that their election be introduced.
For the Courts of Appeal and Cassation, the HRC wishes to introduce special districts that will not be linked to the administrative and territorial division in the Russian Federation.
The Supreme Court should also present its proposals under the presidential mandate.
The HR Committee has finalized proposals that will enhance the independence of Russian justice.
This work was carried out by the HRC on behalf of Vladimir Putin of 3 January 2017, which the President gave after meeting with Council members.
In a meeting with Council members on 8 December 2016, some cases of arbitrary judicial action were discussed, as well as problems of public control in places of detention of citizens (see “Maw” of 9 December).
As a result of the work of the HRC, 25 proposals were made on both the issues of the independence of the judiciary and the identification of judicial errors and the financing of the courts and legal education.
One of the ideas of the Kremlev human rights defenders is to limit the powers of the presidents of the courts to enhance the independence of the other judges.
If the candidate for the position of judge has successfully passed the competition and has received the support of the judicial community, the President of the Court is of the view that he should be presented for appointment without the right to refuse, as the law now permits.
It is also proposed that the President be deprived of the power to assign cases to the judges.
Experts allow this to happen, and a specially written computer program can do so.
The HR Committee also considers that the President is not entitled “to determine the qualifications of the judge, to initiate his disciplinary proceedings and to decide on the establishment of additional material payments”.
At the same time, the Presidential Council believes that it is necessary to move to “election of the presidents of the courts by the judges themselves” and to “exercise their powers for a relatively short period of time with mandatory rotation”.
All the presidents of the courts (from republican to district) are now appointed by the President for six years on the submission of the President of the Supreme Court of the Russian Federation.
In order to protect judges from pressure from regional administrations, the HRC proposes a new way of organizing appeals and cassation before the courts of general jurisdiction.
Their structure is now linked to administrative division in the Russian Federation.
The HRC states that “it is necessary to organize separate courts of appeal and cassation, not at the regional courts level, in the constituent entities of the Russian Federation, but in the judicial districts”.
Experts take the practice of arbitral tribunals as a basis.
They have “judicial districts” that do not coincide with the administrative division in the Russian Federation, but guarantee greater independence from regional officials who have difficulty using “telephone law”.
Justices of the Peace of the Human Rights Council propose to strengthen the participation of people in certain “civil and administrative categories”.
For example, the deprivation of parental rights, the restoration of work, the protection of honour and dignity, the deprivation of driving rights, etc.
“It's just our proposals”, explained "Mighty" member of the HRC, judge of the Constitutional Court retired from Tamara Morszzzkov.
She also recalled that the President ' s mandate was not only for the HR Committee, but also for the Supreme Court (SAF), which had not yet revealed its proposals.
There is still time to carry out the task of the BC (among the perpetrators - the Attorney-General ' s Office and the Human Rights Commissioner in the Russian Federation).
