Red meat, milk products, and chocolate can help to facilitate the OVC.
Red meat and chocolate are commonly considered nightmares for your digestive tract.
But recent studies suggest that diet rich in meat proteins and dairy products can help to ease the symptoms of those suffering from intestinal inflammation.
It is an incurable disease that affects about 1.3 million people in the United States and 300,000 in the United Kingdom, resulting in cramps and stomach swelling, chronic or blood loss, loss of weight, and extreme fatigue.
While it is generally recommended that patients avoid meat and dairy products to alleviate symptoms, researchers at the University of Washington found that the main amino acid of the triptophen protein contributes to the production of immune cells that increase intestinal tolerance.
The lead researcher, Dr. Marco Colonna, explained that the immune cells in the intestines keep harmful germs from entering the body.
Cells capable of firing are balanced by cells that increase tolerance while protecting the body without damaging sensitive tissue.
If the balance is too severe for inflammation, this may lead to intestinal inflammation.
The experiments showed that mice with certain bacteria in their intestines have increased cell tolerance.
And this bacteria needs triptofan, one of the building blocks of the protein, to launch these cells.
Professor Colónna said, "We have established a connection between one species of bacteria - Lactobacillas reuteri - which is part of the normal microbiom of the intestine, and the development of cell populations that increase tolerance.
The more triptofane was contained in mice' diet, the more immunized cells they had."
He suggested that the same thing would work for people: the combination of L. reuteri and the rich tryptofan diet could contribute to a more tolerant and less prone environment in the intestine.
Dr. Louise Servantes-Barragánvas, after studying the variety of immune cell tolerance, found that one group of test mice had these cells, and another group, which belonged to the same line but was kept separately, did not have them.
She suggested that the difference could be caused by intestinal microbiomes -- bacteria, viruses and fungi communities that usually live in the stomach and intestine tract.
The DNA of the mouse intestine cells was separated, and six types of bacteria were found in mice with immune cells but were missing from mice without them.
Muscles grown in a sterile environment that did not have a good microbiom and did not develop this type of immune cell received L. reuteri, and their immune cells came into existence.
To understand how bacteria affect the immune system, researchers grew up L. reutersi in a liquid medium and then transferred small amounts of liquid, without bacteria, to uninformed immune cells separated from mice.
Immune cells have become cells that increase tolerance.
When the active component was separated from the liquid, it turned out to be a by-product of triptofane processing known as indo-3-milic acid.
When researchers doubled the number of triptofane in mouse food, the number of these cells increased by about 50 per cent, but when the level of triptofane was halved, the number of cells also doubled.
Dr. Servantes-Barragán explains that people have the same higher cell tolerance as mice, and most of us have L. reutersi in our stomach tract.
It is not known whether by-products of triptofane from L. reuteri contribute to cell development in humans just like mice, but people suffering from intestinal inflammation have been diagnosed with defects in the genes associated with triptofane.
She says, "Maybe we need to strengthen these cells because these cells depend on burning processes on the inner surface of the intestines.
