A report for the White House cost taxpayers thousands of dollars
According to the records of the armed forces provided by the magazine TIMME, the White House’s decision last month to force a Marine helicopter into the South Lawn on an event dedicated to American industrial production cost taxpayers $24,000.
The White Sikorski VH-3D, known as Marine One, when the President is on board, became a central element of an event in the White House on 17 July at which American construction programmes were shown.
President Donald Trump, Vice-President Mike Pens and the White House senior officials have examined technology products from all fifty states.
The helicopter in Connecticut was taken out by a boat from Man's State, a fire truck from Vicensensin and a heavy truck from Mississippi.
According to the records of the First Marine Helicopter (HMX-1), the White House Military Office ordered the presence of a helicopter in a private order, or “FRAGO”, just 36 hours before the helicopter landed on the South Lawn on the occasion of an “unusual” event.
“I just wanted you to know that you were aware because it was an unusually widely publicized event in the press,” wrote Commander HMX-1 in an e-mail to his superior, the first Deputy Chief of Aviation of the Marine Corps, prior to the event.
The letter indicated that the helicopter would arrive at the South Lawn at about 7 a.m. on 17 July to participate in an event appointed at 3 p.m. and remain there until the lawn was released between 6 p.m. and 9 p.m. on the same day.
The letter adds that, if departure from the White House is delayed, a second crew will be required for return flights, in accordance with the restrictions on hours of work.
The first crew accompanied the helicopter during the event and the unit ' s security officers remained close to the aircraft while it was on the ground.
It is not clear from the records received by TIME whether the second crew was eventually required.
The Hetch Act prohibits federal employees from using public property for political purposes.
According to the records, HMX-1 clarified whether the activity was contrary to the order.
“We asked, among other things, if the Hetch Act was in violation and we were told that it was not,” the commander wrote.
“It looks like you have nowhere to go”, the deputy said.
The event “Docile in America” was declared official by the White House, and has not been covered by Hatch's law.
But even official events have political notes.
During the event, the President made efforts to promote health reform, which was then under development in the Senate, and commended efforts to regulate government regulations.
Use of aircraft known as Marine One and Air Force One for political purposes is hardly new.
The presidents are required to use them for travel.
But it's unusual to ask for them only in the interests of photo-capacity.
The Trump had already been the subject of discussions in February, when the presidential plane had passed in the background during its first election meeting in Melbourne, Florida, and its Twitter account was overwhelmed by complaints about the use of the presidential plane by its predecessor.
“The White House is delighted with the presentation of products from 50 states made by American workers from American materials,” said the Deputy Press Secretary of the White House, Lindsey Walters.
HMX-1 crews often perform training flights around Washington Agglomeration and the South Lawn to train the transport of the President of the United States to the White House with accuracy to an inch.
When Trump was at the G-20 summit in Germany in early July, HMX-1 conducted 58 training missions at the White House.
According to one official, the flight carried out for the American Operation was recorded to the crew on the required training flights per month.
The units also flew 11 additional hours on that day under the “non-presidential support tasks”.
According to the White House, no other exhibit presented at the event was charged to taxpayers.
A representative of Sikorsky reported that the company had not participated in a demonstration of the helicopter on the South Lawn.
HMX-1 does not account for the budget for presidential flights, and it is difficult to determine the exact amount spent on the event.
But according to the Ministry of Defence timeline for fiscal year 2017, the rate of reimbursement to the Ministry of Defence for VH-3D is $24,380 per flight hour.
The unit records 30 minutes of flying time in the air each way from its air base airport at the Quantico Marine Aeronautics Base in Virginia.
The White House states that the real cost of using the helicopter is much lower than that rate.
“It is completely wrong to calculate the value of taxpayers on the basis of an estimated rate of reimbursement,” says Walters.
“These indicative rates include personnel, services and many other irreversible costs, which are included in annual appropriation.”
According to a study conducted in 2015 by REND Corporation, reimbursement rates do not include the cost of personnel, but indeed take into account the cost of fuel, services and costs specified in the contract.
At the time, the former White House spokesman, Sean Spyser, spoke out in defense of the use of the helicopter for the event.
“The idea of showing this week things done in America”, said Spyser.
“And I know that Sikorsky and Connecticut are very proud of the fact that they contribute to national security, and that there are, I suppose, hundreds, if not thousands, whose jobs depend on it.
