There will be two new territories in Russia leading up to social and economic development, “Abasa” and “Novotroitz”.
The relevant rulings of the Government of the Russian Federation will enter into force today, 4 August.
The boundaries and economic activities of the Tora in the territory of the town of Abaza in the Republic of Khakasia are defined.
In the city of 15,000 people, there will be a special legal regime for entrepreneurship, as well as a minimum capital investment of residents, a minimum number of new permanent jobs.
This is expected to attract some 2.5 billion roubles of investment into the city and to create more than 600 new jobs.
The list of economic activities in which Abasa would be subject to a special legal regime for business activities, such as crop production, livestock production, food production, non-alcoholic beverages and clothing, is included.
Already, the Government of the Republic has signed framework agreements for the implementation of 8 investment projects.
It is also planned to reduce the dependency of the Territory on the OOO, the “Abakan mine”.
In January 2017, the authorities in the region reported that Hakasia had complied with all the conditions of Minoconomation for the establishment of a TRE.
The authorities in the Orenburg region have done the same.
There, the city of Novotroitsk will also establish a territory that is ahead of socio-economic development.
This would diversify the monograde economy, reduce its dependence on the roubles roubles of the OO, and create more than 2.3 thousand jobs and attract investment of more than 8 billion roubles.
The list of economic activities in which a special legal regime for entrepreneurs will be in place includes, inter alia, freshwater fishing, food production, medicines and medical supplies.
Novotroitsk was the first of the monocitys of the Orenburg region to be granted the status of the TRA.
Recall that the territory ahead of development is an economic zone with favourable tax conditions, simplified administrative procedures and other privileges that are being created to attract investment to improve the lives of the population.
Among the benefits for residents of the ART are: a profit tax of not more than 5 per cent in the first five years, and not less than 10 per cent in the next five years, social contributions of 7.6 per cent over 10 years, the use of a free customs zone, preferential access to various infrastructures, and preferential rent rates.
